Author: GREY
Vol / Page: 132
Edition:
Quote: Ngahue went to seek a place where his jasper stones might remain in peace, and he found in the sea this island Aotearoa (the northern island of New Zealand).
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1868
Source: Past and Present of NZ
Author: TAYLOR
Vol / Page: 193
Edition:
Quote: The native name for the North Island is, Te Ika a maui[sic] - the fish of Maui ...; they have another ancient name for it in their legends, Aotearoa, but it is now never used. That of the Middle Isle is, Te Wai Pounamu - the water of the green stone.
Notes:

